702617f-a.title: Brooklyn: 18th Avenue - 84th Street
702617f-a.text:
Eighteenth Ave., west side, between 85th and 84th Streets. At the
left, is seen the West End line of the B.M.T., on New Utrecht Ave. At
the right, is the dunther Railway line and private right of way. It was
built in 1863, by C. Godfrey Gunther Fur merchant and Miyor of the City of
New York. It ran from 25th Street and Fifth Ave., (Brooklyn), to Coney
Tsland. It was also known as the Brooklyn Bath and Coney Island R.R.
It is now operated by a trolley Company. At the left, in the triangle,
once stood the foundry of Michael Feigel, builder of street and railroad
Cars.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.
